\section{The Factor-of-Two in Gravitational Lensing}
\label{sec:lensing}
% ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The most famous test of GR over Newtonian gravity is the deflection of
starlight by the Sun, measured by Eddington in 1919.  GR predicts twice
the Newtonian deflection:
\begin{equation}
  \theta_{\rm GR} \;=\; \frac{4GM_\odot}{R_\odot c^2}
  \;\approx\; 1.75\ \text{arcsec},
  \qquad
  \theta_{\rm Newton} \;=\; \frac{2GM_\odot}{R_\odot c^2}
  \;\approx\; 0.875\ \text{arcsec}.
  \label{eq:lensing}
\end{equation}
In standard GR, the factor of 2 arises because the spatial metric $g_{rr}$
contributes equally to light deflection as the time metric $g_{tt}$; a
purely Newtonian (time-only) calculation misses the spatial contribution.

In CPP, the origin of this factor is transparent:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
  \item $|\SSV|_{\rm abs}$ broadcast $\to$ $g_{tt}$ perturbation
    $\to$ time dilation of photon path $\to$ deflection of $0.875$ arcsec.
  \item $\mathbf{\SSV}_{\rm net}$ broadcast $\to$ $g_{rr}$ perturbation
    $\to$ spatial curvature of photon path $\to$ additional $0.875$ arcsec.
  \item Total: $1.75$ arcsec, in exact agreement with observation.
\end{itemize}

\begin{remark}[Retroactive confirmation]
The extended LSP was motivated by the need for a tensorial data structure
to carry GR information --- an internal consistency requirement.  The
precise factor-of-two lensing agreement with Eddington's 1919 measurement
is therefore a \emph{retroactive} prediction: the CPP framework was not
adjusted to fit the lensing data, yet it reproduces the exact factor
automatically from the two-component LSP structure.
\end{remark}

