\section{Geodesic Motion and the Equivalence Principle}
\label{sec:geodesic}
% ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

In GR, free-fall trajectories are geodesics — curves that extremize
proper time.  In CPP, the same result follows from the 12-edge maximum-SSV-gradient
selection rule (Absolute Moment companion, \S3).

At each Absolute Moment tick, a CP at GP $\mathbf{x}$ selects the
edge $i^*$ that maximises $\mathbf{e}_i \cdot \mathbf{\SSV}_{\rm net}$.
In the presence of a gravitational SSV gradient (Newtonian Gravity
companion, Eq.~\ref{eq:DSSV_grav}), the net SSV points preferentially
toward the source mass.  The CP therefore moves preferentially toward
lower gravitational potential — free fall.

The continuum limit of the maximum-gradient selection rule is:
\begin{equation}
  \frac{d^2 x^\mu}{d\tau^2}
  \;+\; \Gamma^\mu_{\nu\rho}\,\frac{dx^\nu}{d\tau}\,\frac{dx^\rho}{d\tau}
  \;=\; 0,
  \label{eq:geodesic}
\end{equation}
where the Christoffel symbols $\Gamma^\mu_{\nu\rho}$ are the CPP
representation of the SSV gradient tensor:
\begin{equation}
  \Gamma^\mu_{\nu\rho} \;\sim\;
  \frac{k}{2}\bigl(\partial_\nu h^\mu{}_\rho
  + \partial_\rho h^\mu{}_\nu
  - \partial^\mu h_{\nu\rho}\bigr),
  \label{eq:Christoffel}
\end{equation}
with $h_{\mu\nu} = \gmn - \eta_{\mu\nu}$ the metric perturbation from
Eqs.~\eqref{eq:gtt}--\eqref{eq:gij}.

The equivalence principle follows immediately: a test particle in
gravitational free fall follows the same trajectory as a particle at
rest in an accelerated frame, because in both cases the net SSV
gradient is identical and the 12-edge selection rule produces the
same path.  No additional postulate is required.



\begin{definition}[Self-consistency condition]
The CPP field equations are the self-consistency requirement: the metric
$\gmn$ reconstructed from the holographic LSP summation
(Eqs.~\eqref{eq:gtt}--\eqref{eq:gij}) must equal the metric that governs
how the LSP packets themselves propagate.
\end{definition}

In the weak-field limit this condition takes the form of the linearised
Einstein equations.  The stress-energy tensor $\Tmn$ is identified with
the LSP source density:
\begin{equation}
  T_{\mu\nu} \;=\; \frac{c^4}{8\pi G}\,\partial^2\hmn
  \;=\; \frac{c^4}{8\pi G}\,\Box\hmn,
  \label{eq:EFE_linear}
\end{equation}
where $\hmn = \gmn - \eta_{\mu\nu}$ is the metric perturbation and
$\Box = -\partial_t^2/c^2 + \nabla^2$ is the d'Alembertian.

The full nonlinear Einstein equations
\begin{equation}
  \Gmn \;=\; \frac{8\pi G}{c^4}\,\Tmn
  \label{eq:EFE}
\end{equation}
emerge in the strong-field regime where the back-reaction of the metric
on LSP propagation becomes non-negligible.  The left side $\Gmn$ (Einstein
tensor) encodes the self-consistency feedback: the curvature produced by
matter also curves the paths of the LSP packets that carry the matter
field.

