\section{Schwarzschild Radius and Black Holes}
\label{sec:BH}
% ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The Schwarzschild radius $r_s = 2GM/c^2$ marks the boundary where
$g_{tt} \to 0$ in Eq.~\eqref{eq:Schwarzschild_CPP}.  In CPP terms, at
$r = r_s$:
\begin{equation}
  k\,\Delta|\SSV|_{\rm abs}(r_s) \;=\; 1
  \qquad \Rightarrow \qquad
  \PSR_{\rm eff}(r_s) \;=\; \frac{\lP}{1+1} \;=\; \frac{\lP}{2}.
\end{equation}
The PSR has contracted to half its vacuum value.  At $r < r_s$, the
strong-field PSR formula predicts $k\cdot\Delta\SSV > 1$, which would
make $g_{tt}$ negative --- the CPP representation of the event horizon.

The PSR formula in the strong-field regime ($\Delta\SSV \sim \SSV_{\rm crit}$)
departs from the Schwarzschild metric and makes predictions that differ
from classical GR.  At $\Delta\SSV = \SSV_{\rm crit}$ (saturation), the
PSR reaches its minimum value $\lP/2$ and no further contraction is
possible.  This introduces a natural ultraviolet cutoff at the Planck scale
--- a potential resolution of the black hole singularity without requiring
quantum gravity beyond what CPP already provides.

